The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 03, 2004 				 Meet mulls strategy to hardsell tourism
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, July 2: The department of tourism plans to aggressively market India overseas in an effort to increase foreign tourist arrivals to 3 million in calendar year 2004 from 2.75 million in the previous year. During January-May this year, there has been a 24.9 per cent growth in foreign tourist arrivals and a 36 per cent increase in foreign exchange earnings.																								The department plans to open offices in China and three to four other destinations. At present, it has 13 overseas offices. A two-day tourism marketing meet in the capital deliberated on the trends and patterns of global tourism to draw up strategies to promote India.																								Industry representatives demanded an improvement in infrastructure like hotel accommodation, air seating capacity and ground transport systems for international and domestic tourists. They drew up a priority list of suggestions that include promoting India as a destination for health tourism, developing rural tourism and strengthening the Incredible India campaign. 
